EasyVisa Analysis¶

Context¶

Business communities in the United States are facing high demand for human resources, but one of the constant challenges is identifying and attracting the right talent, which is perhaps the most important element in remaining competitive. Companies in the United States look for hard-working, talented, and qualified individuals both locally as well as abroad.

The Immigration and Nationality Act (INA) of the US permits foreign workers to come to the United States to work on either a temporary or permanent basis. The act also protects US workers against adverse impacts on their wages or working conditions by ensuring US employers' compliance with statutory requirements when they hire foreign workers to fill workforce shortages. The immigration programs are administered by the Office of Foreign Labor Certification (OFLC).

OFLC processes job certification applications for employers seeking to bring foreign workers into the United States and grants certifications in those cases where employers can demonstrate that there are not sufficient US workers available to perform the work at wages that meet or exceed the wage paid for the occupation in the area of intended employment.

Objective¶

In FY 2016, the OFLC processed 775,979 employer applications for 1,699,957 positions for temporary and permanent labor certifications. This was a nine percent increase in the overall number of processed applications from the previous year. The process of reviewing every case is becoming a tedious task as the number of applicants is increasing every year.

The increasing number of applicants every year calls for a Machine Learning based solution that can help in shortlisting the candidates having higher chances of VISA approval. OFLC has hired the firm EasyVisa for data-driven solutions. You as a data scientist at EasyVisa have to analyze the data provided and, with the help of a classification model:

    1. Facilitate the process of visa approvals.
    1. Recommend a suitable profile for the applicants for whom the visa should be certified or denied based on the drivers that significantly influence the case status.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different attributes of the employee and the employer. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

  • case_id: ID of each visa application
  • continent: Information of continent the employee
  • education_of_employee: Information of education of the employee
  • has_job_experience: Does the employee has any job experience? Y= Yes; N = No
  • requires_job_training: Does the employee require any job training? Y = Yes; N = No
  • no_of_employees: Number of employees in the employer's company
  • yr_of_estab: Year in which the employer's company was established
  • region_of_employment: Information of foreign worker's intended region of employment in the US.
  • prevailing_wage: Average wage paid to similarly employed workers in a specific occupation in the area of intended employment. The purpose of the prevailing wage is to ensure that the foreign worker is not underpaid compared to other workers offering the same or similar service in the same area of employment.
  • unit_of_wage: Unit of prevailing wage. Values include Hourly, Weekly, Monthly, and Yearly.
  • full_time_position: Is the position of work full-time? Y = Full-Time Position; N = Part-Time Position
  • case_status: Flag indicating if the Visa was certified or denied

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.


def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram


# function to create labeled barplots


def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

# function to plot stacked bar chart


def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left",
        frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

Data PreProcessing¶

Feature Engineering¶

We can add a few features that might be helpful in the context of this problem.

  • employees_per_year -> Captures the relationship between company size (no_of_employees) and maturity (yr_of_estab). Helps identify whether larger, older companies are more likely to succeed in certification.

  • normalized_wage -> The original prevailing_wage column has wages expressed in different units (e.g., hourly, weekly, monthly, yearly). Normalizing wages converts them into a consistent unit (e.g., yearly), enabling meaningful comparisons across all rows.

  • log_prevailing_wage -> Reduces skewness in the wage distribution, making it easier for models to identify meaningful patterns. Helps handle extreme values in normalized_wage.

  • wage_per_employee -> Highlights efficiency or cost per employee, which could influence case outcomes. Provides insight into whether higher wages per employee correlate with certification success.

In [16]:
# Inspect unique units
print(data['unit_of_wage'].unique())

['Hour' 'Year' 'Week' 'Month']
  • Wages are in hourly, weekly, monthly and yearly basis.
  • We will convert these to yearly basis.
In [5]:
# Define conversion factors
conversion_factors = {
    'Hour': 2080, #Assumes a full-time work schedule of 40 hours per week and 52 weeks per year
    'Week': 52, #52 weeks per year
    'Month': 12, #12 months per year
    'Year': 1 # yearly wages
}

# Normalize prevailing_wage to yearly wages
data['normalized_wage'] = data['prevailing_wage'] * data['unit_of_wage'].map(conversion_factors)
In [6]:
# Creating new features

#capture relationship between company size (no_of_employees) and maturity (yr_of_estab)
data['employees_per_year'] = data['no_of_employees'] / (2025 - data['yr_of_estab'])

#Reduce skewness of normalized wage
data['log_prevailing_wage'] = np.log1p(data['normalized_wage'])

#Highlights efficiency or cost per employee
data['wage_per_employee'] = data['normalized_wage'] / data['no_of_employees']

  • The number of rows with negative values is small (e.g., <5% of the dataset), dropping them is a simple and effective solution.
  • This avoids introducing assumptions or bias into the data.
In [7]:

Handling Outliers¶
  • Handling outliers ensures the dataset is clean, representative, and suitable for training robust models without bias from extreme values.
  • Outliers in no_of_employees and normalized_wage can skew model predictions and affect decision boundaries.
  • Capping extreme values ensures the model focuses on meaningful patterns rather than being influenced by rare, extreme cases.
  • Outliers can lead to overfitting, especially in tree-based models, by creating splits that cater to rare values.
  • We use +- 1.5 IQR range to filter out the outliers.
In [8]:
# Step 3: Handle Outliers using 1.5 * IQR
def cap_outliers(df, column):
    Q1 = df[column].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = df[column].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    df[column] = np.where(df[column] < lower_bound, lower_bound, df[column])
    df[column] = np.where(df[column] > upper_bound, upper_bound, df[column])

print(f"Range for 'normalized_wage': {data['normalized_wage'].min()} to {data['normalized_wage'].max()}")

# Apply outlier capping to numerical columns
cap_outliers(data, 'no_of_employees')
cap_outliers(data, 'normalized_wage')

# Check the updated ranges

Model Building¶

Model evaluation criterion¶

We will be using Precision as a metric for our model performance on Certified class because¶

  • You want to be confident that cases you predict as Certified are truly eligible.
  • A false positive (predicting "Certified" when it would be denied) wastes time and effort.

Since your model will be used to shortlist candidates for easy approvals, it must trust the prediction of “Certified”.

  • Helping prioritize candidates most likely to get certified
  • Reducing effort in manually reviewing "almost certain approvals"

What we should focus on ?¶

Correctly identifying certified candidates Reducing false denials (i.e., don't wrongly discard good profiles)

How to reduce this loss i.e need to reduce False Positives?¶

  • Company wants precision to be maximized i.e. we need to reduce the number of false positives.

# loop through all models to get the mean cross validated score

# unbiased manner, providing insights into its ability to generalize beyond the training data
print("\n" "Cross-Validation Performance:" "\n")
for name, model in models:
    scoring = "recall"

    # Setting number of splits equal to 5
    kfold = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=1)
    cv_result = cross_val_score(
        estimator=model, X=X_train, y=y_train, scoring=scoring, cv=kfold
    )
    results.append(cv_result)
    names.append(name)
    print("{}: {:.2f}".format(name, cv_result.mean() * 100))


print("\n" "Validation Performance:" "\n")

    _ = model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    score = recall_score(y_val, model.predict(X_val))
    scores.append(score)
    print("{}: {:.2f}".format(name, score*100))

Hyperparameter Tuning¶

  • Here is the snapshot indicating the performance of best performing models across original and oversampled data.
  • This doesn't include any model on undersampled data since they performance was bad compared to models trained on orginal and oversampled data.

  • GBM has the most consistent performance with stable results.
  • Adaboost has the highest performance on validation set for original data with minimal variability.
  • Xgboost has relatively inferior performance but is still much better than models such as Bagging, decision trees etc.
  • All models seem to perform consistently on both original data and oversampled data.

We will tune GBM on original and oversampled data, Adaboost on original data and Xgboost model on oversampled data using GridSearchCV and RandomizedSearchCV. We will also compare the performance and time taken by these two methods - grid search and randomized search.

First let's create two functions to calculate different metrics and confusion matrix, so that we don't have to use the same code repeatedly for each model.

# defining a function to compute different metrics to check performance of a classification model built using sklearn
def model_performance_classification_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Function to compute different metrics to check classification model performance

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # to compute Accuracy
    recall = recall_score(target, pred)  # to compute Recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred)  # to compute Precision
    f1 = f1_score(target, pred)  # to compute F1-score

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Accuracy": acc,
            "Recall": recall,
            "Precision": precision,
            "F1": f1,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf
In [21]:
def confusion_matrix_sklearn(model, predictors, target):
    """
    To plot the confusion_matrix with percentages

    model: classifier
    predictors: independent variables
    target: dependent variable
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(predictors)
    cm = confusion_matrix(target, y_pred)
    labels = np.asarray(
        [
            ["{0:0.0f}".format(item) + "\n{0:.2%}".format(item / cm.flatten().sum())]
            for item in cm.flatten()
        ]
    ).reshape(2, 2)

    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="")
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")
In [22]:
def run_hyperparameter_search(model, param_grid, X, y, search_type='grid', scoring='accuracy', cv=5, n_iter=50):
    """
    Run GridSearchCV or RandomizedSearchCV for hyperparameter tuning.
    
    Parameters:
    - model: Base model to optimize.
    - param_grid: Dictionary of hyperparameters to search.
    - X_train: Training feature set.
    - y_train: Training target set.
    - search_type: 'grid' for GridSearchCV or 'random' for RandomizedSearchCV (default: 'grid').
    - scoring: Metric to optimize (default: 'accuracy').
    - cv: Number of cross-validation folds (default: 5).
    - n_iter: Number of iterations for RandomizedSearchCV (default: 50).
    
    Returns:
    - best_params: Dictionary of best hyperparameters.
    - best_model: Trained model with best hyperparameters.
    """
    if search_type == 'grid':
        search = GridSearchCV(
            estimator=model,
            param_grid=param_grid,
            scoring=scoring,
            cv=cv,
            verbose=1,
            n_jobs=-1
        )
    elif search_type == 'random':
        search = RandomizedSearchCV(
            estimator=model,
            param_distributions=param_grid,
            scoring=scoring,
            cv=cv,
            n_iter=n_iter,
            random_state=1,
            verbose=1,
            n_jobs=-1
        )
    else:
        raise ValueError("Invalid search_type. Use 'grid' or 'random'.")
    
    # Fit the search object
    search.fit(X, y)
    
    return search.best_params_, search.best_estimator_
In [39]:
def run_and_display_results(model, param_grid, X_train, y_train, X_val, y_val, search_type='grid', scoring='accuracy', cv=5, n_iter=50):
    """
    Run hyperparameter search for a data + model combination and display results.
    
    Parameters:
    - model: Base model to optimize.
    - param_grid: Dictionary of hyperparameters to search.
    - X_train: Training feature set.
    - y_train: Training target set.
    - X_val: Validation feature set.
    - y_val: Validation target set.
    - search_type: 'grid' for GridSearchCV or 'random' for RandomizedSearchCV (default: 'grid').
    - scoring: Metric to optimize (default: 'accuracy').
    - cv: Number of cross-validation folds (default: 5).
    - n_iter: Number of iterations for RandomizedSearchCV (default: 50).
    
    Returns:
    - None (prints results directly).
    """
    # Run hyperparameter search
    best_params, best_model = run_hyperparameter_search(
        model=model,
        param_grid=param_grid,
        X=X_train,
        y=y_train,
        search_type=search_type,
        scoring=scoring,
        cv=cv,
        n_iter=n_iter
    )
    

    # Extract the class type of the base model
    model_class = type(model)
    
    # Reinitialize the model with best parameters
    tuned_model = model_class(**best_params, random_state=1)

    tuned_model.fit(X_train, y_train)


    # Print results
    print(f"\n\nModel: {model.__class__.__name__}")
    print(f"\nSearch Type: {search_type}")
    print(f"\nBest Parameters:\n {pd.DataFrame(best_params.items(), columns=["Hyperparameter", "Value"])}\n")

    # Checking model's performance on training set
    train_metrics = model_performance_classification_sklearn(
        tuned_model, X_train, y_train
    )
    print("\nTraining metrics:")
    print(train_metrics)

    # Checking model's performance on validation set
    val_metrics = model_performance_classification_sklearn(
        tuned_model, X_val, y_val
        )
    print("\nValidation metrics:")
    print(val_metrics)


    # creating confusion matrix
    print("\nConfusion Matrix:")
    confusion_matrix_sklearn(tuned_model, X_val, y_val)

    return tuned_model, train_metrics, val_metrics

Conclusion and Insights¶

Key Takeaways from Model and Data Analysis¶

1. Education Level is the most significant predictor of visa approval¶

  • Candidates with High School education are significantly more likely to have their visa applications approved.
  • Advanced education levels (e.g., Master's) also positively impact approval likelihood, but to a lesser extent.

Recommendation: Focus on prioritizing applications from candidates with High School education during the initial screening process.

2. Job Experience strongly correlates with visa approval¶

  • Candidates with prior job experience (has_job_experience_Y) are significantly more likely to have their applications approved.
  • Lack of job experience reduces the likelihood of approval.

Recommendation: Prioritize applications from candidates with relevant job experience.

3. Wage-related attributes moderately impact approval likelihood¶

  • Prevailing wage and unit of wage (Year) are moderately important predictors.
  • Higher wages correlate with better approval chances, but they are secondary to education and job experience.

Recommendation: Use wage-related attributes as supplementary criteria for prioritization. Highlight applications with competitive wages during the evaluation process.

4. Geographic attributes have limited influence¶

  • Features like region of employment and continent have limited impact on approval likelihood.
  • These factors are less critical compared to individual-level attributes like education and job experience.

Recommendation: Deprioritize geographic attributes during the evaluation process to streamline decision-making.

5. Full-Time Positions slightly improve approval chances¶

  • Candidates applying for full-time positions (full_time_position_Y) are slightly more likely to be approved.
  • Part-time positions have lower approval likelihood.

Recommendation: Focus on applications for full-time positions during prioritization.

6. Engineered features have limited predictive power¶

  • Features like employees_per_year, log_prevailing_wage, and wage_per_employee have low importance in the model.
  • These features do not significantly improve predictive accuracy.

Recommendation: Avoid relying heavily on engineered features for decision-making. Focus on core attributes like education and job experience.

7. Automated Candidate Shortlisting can reduce workload¶

  • The best-performing model (e.g., XGBoost) can be used to automate the scoring and ranking of candidates based on their likelihood of approval.
  • This will help visa offices prioritize high-probability applications and reduce manual workload.

Recommendation: Implement an automated scoring system to rank candidates based on approval likelihood. Use this system to streamline the evaluation process and focus resources on high-priority applications.
